		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71fa1f9682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>7:12.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Subjects of expert testimony—Physical condition</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Opinion testimony is admissible to show physical condition. <eos/>
						<bos/>A lay witness may state an opinion about physical condition, such as that a person appeared to be very sick,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b1533074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] if he includes the facts on which his opinion is based.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b1533174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] Only experts may offer opinions concerning diagnosis, treatment, effect, and continuance of a person&apos;s physical condition.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b1533274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1997050769" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idc2d6c6274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Hutcheson v. Daniels</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b17a4074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>
						<?page no="198"?>] the plaintiff noticed problems with his left wrist a few days after a collision with defendant and sought medical treatment within four months of the onset of these symptoms. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals held that a jury could conclude from common knowledge that a causal connection existed between the plaintiff&apos;s injury and the accident in light of the short lapse of time between the collision, the onset of symptoms, and receipt of medical treatment. <eos/>
						<bos/>The Court cited <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1990142446" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idc2e2fb274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Madden v. Solomon</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78b17a4174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] where it also held that a jury could determine, without expert testimony, that medical expenses after an automobile collision were related to injuries sustained in the collision.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>However, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1987022299" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="Idc2f1a1374d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Eberhart v. Morris Brown College</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b17a4274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] the court held that a medical expert was necessary to establish a causal connection between the plaintiff&apos;s injury and his football career due to a gap of several years.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Since a witness can testify about the extent of another person&apos;s intoxication based on his observation,[<footnote.reference refid="I78b17a4374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>] the court held in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1990026111" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Idc30529274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Chance v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I78b1a15074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">8</footnote.reference>] that law enforcement officers could testify that the defendant in a driving-under-the-influence (DUI) case was both under the influence of alcohol and that the extent of the defendant&apos;s drunkenness rendered him “a less safe driver.”<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The trial court cannot discount expert testimony providing evidence of specific causation where a plaintiff is overexposed to a dangerous chemical without conducting the requisite <ital>Daubert</ital> analysis. <eos/>
						<bos/>Further, such proof that exposure to a toxic chemical is dangerous renders moot the question of how many doses it takes to cause the disease, since the only cause of the disease is exposure to the chemical.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b1a15174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The Court of Appeals has rejected expert testimony regarding a defendant&apos;s post-traumatic stress disorder as irrelevant to the issue of criminal intent.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b1a15274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>The Court has held that expert testimony is necessary to support a defendant&apos;s claim of justification where they are claiming battered person syndrome.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I78b1a15374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
